Historically, '''bannimus''' ([[Latin language|Latin]]: "we banish") was the form of [[Expulsion (academia)|expulsion]] of any individual from the [[University of Oxford]], by putting the proctorial edict up in some public place, as a denunciation or promulgation of it. It also served to prevent the individual from claiming the cause of expulsion was unknown.
Individuals can still be expelled today, as well as ''rusticated'', that is, when a student is sent down or banished from the University for a period of time before being allowed to return and further their education.
The term ''bannimus'' is related to ''bannition'', which is the general expulsion of an individual from a university.
